        <body>
            <div type="edition">
                <div type="textpart" subtype="chapter">
                    <ab><title>Exodus 36</title>
                        <milestone unit="line" xml:id="line-3-2" n="3" prev="ADub.III.73.002.035.trl.xml#line-3-1" />
                        <l n="1">And Bezalel and Oholiab
                            <milestone unit="line" n="4" />
                            and every wise hearted man in whose heart the Lord has put wisdom and understanding
                            <milestone unit="line" n="5" />
                            to know how to do all the work of the service of the Holy
                            <milestone unit="line" n="6" />
                            shall do according to all that the Lord had commanded.</l>
                        <l n="2">And Moses called
                            <milestone unit="line" n="7" />
                            Bezalel and Oholiab, and every wise hearted man in whose
                            <milestone unit="line" n="8" />
                            heart the Lord had put wisdom, everyone whose heart guided
                            <milestone unit="line" n="9" />
                            him to come for the work, to do it.</l>
                        <l n="3">
                            <milestone unit="line" n="10" />
                            And they took from in front of Moses all the heave offering that
                            <milestone unit="line" n="11" />
                            the children of Israel had brought for the work of the holy service,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="12" />
                            to make it. And the children of Israel even brought him
                            <milestone unit="line" n="13" />
                            freewill offerings at every dawn.</l>
                        <l n="4">And
                            <milestone unit="line" n="14" />
                            all the wise men who were doing all the holy work
                            <milestone unit="line" n="15" />
                            came, every man from his work that they were doing.</l>
                        <l n="5">
                            <milestone unit="line" n="16" />
                            And they said to Moses, saying, ‘The people are bringing
                            <milestone unit="line" n="17" />
                            more than needed for the service of the work which the Lord commanded
                            <milestone unit="line" n="18" />
                            to make.’</l>
                        <l n="6">And Moses gave command, and they caused a voice to pass
                            <milestone unit="line" n="19" />
                            throughout the camp, saying, ‘Let no man or woman do any more work
                            <milestone unit="line" n="20" />
                            for the heave offering of the Holy.’ And the people ceased bringing.</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="21" />
                        <l n="7">And the work they had was sufficient for them
                            <milestone unit="page" n="148v" />
                            <milestone unit="line" n="1" />
                            to do it and to be left over.</l>
                        <l n="8">And every wise
                            <milestone unit="line" n="2" />
                            hearted man among them who were doing the work made the tabernacle of ten
                            <milestone unit="line" n="3" />
                            curtains of twined linen, and of blue and purple and scarlet
                            <milestone unit="line" n="4" />
                            silk — they made them with cherubim of embroiderer’s work.</l>
                        <l n="9">
                            <milestone unit="line" n="5" />
                            The length of one curtain twenty-eight cubits, and
                            <milestone unit="line" n="6" />
                            the breadth of one curtain four cubits:
                            <milestone unit="line" n="7" />
                            on size for all curtains.</l>
                        <l n="10">And he coupled the five
                            <milestone unit="line" n="8" />
                            curtains one to another, and he coupled the other five curtains one
                            <milestone unit="line" n="9" />
                            to another.</l>
                        <l n="11">And he made loops of blue on the edge
                            <milestone unit="line" n="10" />
                            of the one outmost curtain in the place of being coupled. He did so
                            <milestone unit="line" n="11" />
                            in the edge of the second outmost curtain in the place of being
                            coupled.</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="12" />
                        <l n="12">He made fifty loops in one curtain, and
                            <milestone unit="line" n="13" />
                            he made fifty loops in the edge of the second curtain
                            <milestone unit="line" n="14" />
                            in the place of being coupled. The loops were opposite one
                            <milestone unit="line" n="15" />
                            another.</l>
                        <l n="13">And he made fifty hooks of gold,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="16" />
                            and coupled the curtains one to another with the hooks. And
                            <milestone unit="line" n="17" />
                            the tabernacle was one.</l>
                        <l n="14">And he made curtains of
                            <milestone unit="line" n="18" />
                            goats’ hair for the tent over the tabernacle. He made them eleven
                            curtains.</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="19" />
                        <l n="15">The length of one curtain thirty cubits,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="20" />
                            and four cubits the breadth of one curtain:
                            <milestone unit="line" n="21" />
                            on size for the eleven curtains.</l>
                        <l n="16">And he coupled five curtains
                            <milestone unit="page" n="149r" />
                            <milestone unit="line" n="1" />
                            separately, and six curtains separately.</l>
                        <l n="17">And he made fifty
                            <milestone unit="line" n="2" />
                            loops on the edge of the one outmost in the place of being coupled,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="3" />
                            and fifty loops he made on the edge of the second
                            <milestone unit="line" n="4" />
                            connecting curtain.</l>
                        <l n="18">And he made fifty hooks
                            <milestone unit="line" n="5" />
                            of bronze to couple the tent together, to be one.</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="6" />
                        <l n="19">And he made a covering for the tent of rams’ skins
                            <milestone unit="line" n="7" />
                            dyed red, and a covering of porpoise skins above that.</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="8" />
                        <l n="20">And he made boards for the tabernacle of acacia
                            <milestone unit="line" n="9" />
                            wood, standing.</l>
                        <l n="21">Ten cubits the length
                            <milestone unit="line" n="10" />
                            of a board, and a cubit and a half the breadth of a
                            <milestone unit="line" n="11" />
                            board.</l>
                        <l n="22">One board had two tenons
                            <milestone unit="line" n="12" />
                            that fit together: so he made for all the boards
                            <milestone unit="line" n="13" />
                            of the tabernacle.</l>
                        <l n="23">And he made boards for the tabernacle:
                            <milestone unit="line" n="14" />
                            twenty boards for the south side, southward.</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="15" />
                        <l n="24">And he made forty bases of silver under the twenty
                            <milestone unit="line" n="16" />
                            boards, two bases under one board
                            <milestone unit="line" n="17" />
                            for its two tenons, and two bases under one
                            <milestone unit="line" n="18" />
                            board for its two tenons.</l>
                        <l n="25">And
                            <milestone unit="line" n="19" />
                            for the other side of the tabernacle, toward the north side, he made
                            <milestone unit="line" n="20" />
                            twenty boards,</l>
                        <l n="26">And their forty bases
                            <milestone unit="line" n="21" />
                            of silver, two bases under one board, and two
                            <milestone unit="page" n="149v" />
                            <milestone unit="line" n="1" />
                            bases under one board.</l>
                        <l n="27">And for the edges
                            <milestone unit="line" n="2" />
                            of the tabernacle, westward, he made six boards.</l>
                        <l n="28">
                            <milestone unit="line" n="3" />
                            And he made two boards for the corners of the tabernacle in the
                            edges.</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="4" />
                        <l n="29">And they were in one line at the bottom and integrated
                            <milestone unit="line" n="5" />
                            in one line at the top of it, to one ring. He made it so
                            <milestone unit="line" n="6" />
                            for the two of them, for the two corners.</l>
                        <l n="30">And there were
                            <milestone unit="line" n="7" />
                            eight boards, and their bases of silver; sixteen bases,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="8" />
                            two bases under one board, and two bases
                            <milestone unit="line" n="9" />
                            under one board.</l>
                        <l n="31">And he made bars
                            <milestone unit="line" n="10" />
                            of acacia wood: five for the boards of the one side of the
                            tabernacle,</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="11" />
                        <l n="32">And five bars for the boards of the second side
                            <milestone unit="line" n="12" />
                            of the tabernacle, and five bars for the boards of the tabernacle
                            <milestone unit="line" n="13" />
                            at the edges, westward.</l>
                        <l n="33">And he made the middle
                            <milestone unit="line" n="14" />
                            bar in midst of the boards to fill |the space|
                            <milestone unit="line" n="15" />
                            from end to end.</l>
                        <l n="34">And
                            <milestone unit="line" n="16" />
                            he overlaid the boards with gold, and made their rings of gold,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="17" />
                            places for the bars, and overlaid the bars
                            <milestone unit="line" n="18" />
                            with gold.</l>
                        <l n="35">And he made a veil of blue
                            <milestone unit="line" n="19" />
                            and purple and scarlet silk, and twined linen:
                            <milestone unit="line" n="20" />
                            he made it embroiderer’s work with cherubim.</l>
                        <l n="36">And he made for it
                            <milestone unit="line" n="21" />
                            four pillars of acacia wood, and overlaid them with gold:
                            <milestone unit="page" n="150r" />
                            <milestone unit="line" n="1" />
                            and their hooks were of gold, and he cast for them four bases
                            <milestone unit="line" n="2" />
                            of silver.</l>
                        <l n="37">And he made a cover for the door of the tent
                            <milestone unit="line" n="3" />
                            of blue and purple and scarlet silk, and twined linen,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="4" />
                            of needlework,</l>
                        <l n="38">And the five pillars of it
                            <milestone unit="line" n="5" />
                            with their hooks, and he overlaid their capitals and
                            <milestone unit="line" n="6" />
                            their bands with gold, and their five bases were of bronze.</l>
                    </ab>
                </div>
            </div>
        </body>
